data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code for .NET 8.

## Usage Inventory

| Location | API | Pattern |
|----------|-----|---------|
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption — wakes thread from `WaitOne()` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop fallback — forcibly kills thread |
| `RunLoop()` | `while (true)` | Cancellable work loop — needs cooperative exit |

Both `Thread.Abort()` (`SYSLIB0006` / `PlatformNotSupportedException`) and `Thread.Interrupt()` (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) must be replaced with `CancellationToken` signaling.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index: 0 = new event, 1 = cancellation
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1)
                break; // cancellation requested

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race condition
            // where multiple Enqueue calls between signals lost items)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // signals token.WaitHandle, waking WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for cooperative exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Original | Migrated | Reason |
|----------|----------|--------|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative loop exit |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cancelling sets `token.WaitHandle`, unblocking `WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed | No longer needed — the loop exits cooperatively |
| Single `Dequeue` | Drain loop | Fixes pre-existing bug: rapid `Enqueue` calls could strand items |
| No disposal | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` leak if not disposed |

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`WaitOne` doesn't check cancellation** — `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` will block forever if you only cancel the token. You **must** use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` as a second handle.

2. **Cancellation is not immediate** — If `Handle(item)` is long-running, the thread won't exit until it finishes and loops back to the `IsCancellationRequested` check. If `Handle` also needs to be cancellable, pass the token into it.

3. **Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — It allocates a `WaitHandle` and timer internally. Leaking it leaks OS handles.

4. **No forced termination fallback exists** — If `Handle()` hangs on uncooperative code (native call, third-party library), the thread will never exit. The only option is to move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill`.

## Modern Idiomatic Alternative

If you're rewriting rather than porting, `Channel<T>` eliminates the manual synchronization entirely:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _task;

    public void Start()
    {
        _task = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // timeout fallback
        if (_task is not null) await _task;
    }

    public void Dispose() => _cts.Dispose();
    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

The `Channel<T>` version has no locks, no `ManualResetEvent`, and no `Thread` — the framework handles all synchronization. Use this if the API surface can change to async.
